WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.600
Orla Doyle on creating reproducible static reports.

00:00:04.800 --> 00:00:05.100
Cool.

00:00:05.100 --> 00:00:05.800
Thanks very much.

00:00:11.100 --> 00:00:11.300
Cool.

00:00:11.300 --> 00:00:12.000
Thanks everyone.

00:00:12.200 --> 00:00:14.700
Really nice to be here all the way from Dublin.

00:00:15.400 --> 00:00:18.100
Good way to fight the jet lag is have a talk in the afternoon

00:00:18.100 --> 00:00:20.000
because the adrenaline kind of overrides that.

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:25.200
So I'm going to talk about a process of automated reporting

00:00:25.500 --> 00:00:27.600
and I'm also going to talk a little bit about how we work

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:29.200
in the pharmaceutical industry.

00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:32.000
Just to give you some insight into kind of what's a bit

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:33.900
different about some of the ways that we work.

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:36.400
So these are my disclaimers.

00:00:36.700 --> 00:00:39.299
So these views are my own and don't represent the company

00:00:39.299 --> 00:00:40.000
that I work for.

00:00:41.799 --> 00:00:45.500
So pharmaceutical industry does lots of things, but the part

00:00:45.500 --> 00:00:48.000
of the pharmaceutical industry that I work in is clinical

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:49.000
drug development.

00:00:49.299 --> 00:00:52.000
And so what we're trying to do is we're trying to develop

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:55.500
new medicines and produce robust evidence to understand

00:00:55.500 --> 00:00:58.700
whether or not these medicines are safe and effective.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:00.799
So are they safe and do they work?

00:01:01.200 --> 00:01:04.800
And we do this in a very regulated way and that's not something

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:05.900
we're trying to get rid of.

00:01:06.199 --> 00:01:07.500
We like to sleep at night.

00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:09.400
So we welcome a lot of that regulation.

00:01:09.699 --> 00:01:13.199
It makes sure that we adhere to really high standards and

00:01:13.199 --> 00:01:15.400
that our work is indeed reliable.

00:01:16.400 --> 00:01:18.599
And in order to do this, we work with lots of different people.

00:01:19.099 --> 00:01:21.500
So we work with people who have very different backgrounds

00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:24.699
to perhaps folks like ourselves in this room and it's a very

00:01:24.699 --> 00:01:27.000
multidisciplinary environment.

00:01:27.400 --> 00:01:30.699
So when we want to review this evidence together, we often

00:01:30.699 --> 00:01:33.599
focus on things like static reports and people here like

00:01:33.599 --> 00:01:37.199
yawn, how boring, move on, but actually when you have people

00:01:37.199 --> 00:01:40.300
who come from very different disciplines, sometimes those

00:01:40.300 --> 00:01:43.500
static reports are a lower barrier to actually getting

00:01:43.500 --> 00:01:46.500
the work done that we need to get done, which is understanding

00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:48.000
are our drugs safe and effective.

00:01:49.900 --> 00:01:52.500
Then when we think about this word regulated, what does that

00:01:52.500 --> 00:01:53.099
really mean?

00:01:53.599 --> 00:01:56.599
It means lots of things across the industry that we work in,

00:01:56.900 --> 00:01:59.699
but again, if we're thinking about statistics or data science

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:02.300
for us, there's kind of three main pillars to it.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:04.400
Is what we're doing traceable?

00:02:04.599 --> 00:02:07.699
So if I'm working on a piece of data, do I understand the

00:02:07.699 --> 00:02:08.899
lineage of that data?

00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:13.199
What happened to it before I got it and did the right things

00:02:13.199 --> 00:02:14.000
happen to it?

00:02:14.899 --> 00:02:16.399
Is my work reproducible?

00:02:16.899 --> 00:02:19.100
So we submit something to a health authority.

00:02:19.100 --> 00:02:20.000
They review it.

00:02:20.199 --> 00:02:21.600
Perhaps they have some queries.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Maybe that query is a couple of weeks down the line.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:25.899
Maybe it's a couple of years down the line.

00:02:26.199 --> 00:02:29.199
We want to be able to come back to our work, understand if I

00:02:29.199 --> 00:02:31.899
have a static figure, what's behind it?

00:02:31.899 --> 00:02:33.199
Could I reproduce it?

00:02:33.399 --> 00:02:34.500
And could I tweak it, right?

00:02:34.500 --> 00:02:36.100
So that might be what we're thinking about.

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:37.399
Is it accurate?

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:40.100
I mean, that's a big, big part of what we do.

00:02:40.899 --> 00:02:44.500
Often we think about going from writing a specification to

00:02:44.500 --> 00:02:48.199
me, mostly as a human, interpreting that specification

00:02:48.600 --> 00:02:50.600
into code, into an output.

00:02:50.899 --> 00:02:53.000
All those steps we want to think about accuracy.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.199
So not just is the number correct, but did I do the right

00:02:56.199 --> 00:02:57.000
analysis?

00:02:58.300 --> 00:03:00.000
So they're the kind of things that we think about.

00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:03.199
So again, a lot of it sounds like we take a lot of these

00:03:03.199 --> 00:03:06.600
steps very carefully and you might be thinking that sounds

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:10.399
like a hard industry to have change and sometimes it is and

00:03:10.399 --> 00:03:13.699
we don't always take change up very rapidly.

00:03:14.300 --> 00:03:17.100
Often we move a little bit more slowly and more carefully,

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:20.199
again, because of that regulated nature and because of the

00:03:20.199 --> 00:03:23.199
high impact of us being right or wrong in our work.

00:03:23.399 --> 00:03:26.600
So an error, making a mistake that propagates through to

00:03:26.600 --> 00:03:29.600
something that affects a patient, is something that is we

00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:31.500
want to avoid at all costs, right?

00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:34.399
So again, we're kind of embracing that regulation, but

00:03:34.399 --> 00:03:37.000
also trying to think about what does it mean to change?

00:03:37.500 --> 00:03:39.699
And I think I want to talk today about two different types

00:03:39.699 --> 00:03:40.399
of change.

00:03:40.800 --> 00:03:43.600
So I think if you talk to any people here from the pharma

00:03:43.600 --> 00:03:48.000
industry, we're all a little bit in different phases of these

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:48.899
big changes.

00:03:49.699 --> 00:03:53.300
Moving from proprietary tools to open source tools, thinking

00:03:53.300 --> 00:03:56.899
about moving from static to dynamic, there's change everywhere.

00:03:57.300 --> 00:04:00.000
Thinking about changing the types of compute environments

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:00.899
that we work in, right?

00:04:00.899 --> 00:04:05.300
So we're in this big kind of phase of change and it's taking

00:04:05.300 --> 00:04:07.800
us a little bit of time and we're all at different phases.

00:04:08.399 --> 00:04:10.399
But there's also non-disruptive change and I think

00:04:10.399 --> 00:04:13.100
non-disruptive change, it keeps you energized, it keeps your

00:04:13.100 --> 00:04:16.399
teams energized and it also prepares you for that big

00:04:16.399 --> 00:04:18.000
destination that you want to get to.

00:04:18.700 --> 00:04:22.799
And I think the example today is a nice example of changing

00:04:22.799 --> 00:04:26.100
something in how we work that makes it better for someone

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:29.399
like a statistician, but ultimately we end up with the same

00:04:29.399 --> 00:04:31.799
end product, which is our static report.

00:04:32.200 --> 00:04:35.600
So we don't perhaps need to do so much stakeholder engagement.

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:39.100
We don't maybe need to do so much change of the entire process.

00:04:39.299 --> 00:04:42.000
Maybe what we're doing is adding a pathway instead of changing

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:43.000
the entire pathway.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.200
And so this is kind of a very simplified version of how we

00:04:48.200 --> 00:04:51.100
work and again, I think we've seen that diagram, which is

00:04:51.100 --> 00:04:53.799
not that dissimilar in several people's talks today.

00:04:54.100 --> 00:04:57.399
How do we get from an idea to a result?

00:04:57.899 --> 00:05:00.399
And so again, we think about code, that could be the code

00:05:00.399 --> 00:05:02.899
that we're specifically writing or code that we're consuming

00:05:02.899 --> 00:05:04.700
from, you know, an open source package.

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:07.600
We have a lot of metadata in how we work.

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:09.000
We work with standards.

00:05:09.299 --> 00:05:11.899
So it could be, well, the footer of that table should look

00:05:11.899 --> 00:05:14.600
like this or it could be, you know, the structure of your

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:16.399
data model should look a bit like this.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:18.799
And then we have the input data itself.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:21.899
So what are we going to consume in order to derive those

00:05:21.899 --> 00:05:23.600
outputs that we are so interested in?

00:05:24.500 --> 00:05:27.500
We have this kind of magic stuff in the middle and these

00:05:27.500 --> 00:05:30.100
are our workflow managers, our execution models.

00:05:30.100 --> 00:05:32.200
I think we have lots of different names for these things,

00:05:32.700 --> 00:05:34.700
but these are things like make facilities.

00:05:34.700 --> 00:05:37.100
These are things that help us with reproducibility.

00:05:37.399 --> 00:05:40.600
They help us with audit trails and they help us to produce

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:43.899
our outputs in a way that we feel far more confident that

00:05:43.899 --> 00:05:45.799
they are traceable, reproducible.

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:48.700
The accuracy really is done by the human, I would say.

00:05:49.700 --> 00:05:51.799
And we want to get to maybe two places.

00:05:51.899 --> 00:05:54.100
So dynamic outputs and static outputs.

00:05:54.700 --> 00:05:56.399
And we've done all this hard work, right?

00:05:56.399 --> 00:05:59.000
We've done all this hard work to make sure things are

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.399
reproducible, to make sure we have the audit trail.

00:06:01.899 --> 00:06:05.100
And then we take the sledgehammer of control C and control

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:10.100
B and we copy and paste things from mystery location.

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:14.700
Two words document and that feels very fundamentally wrong

00:06:14.700 --> 00:06:16.799
given all the work that has gone before it.

00:06:17.500 --> 00:06:21.299
And it doesn't scale, it's error prone and it's a frustrating

00:06:21.299 --> 00:06:22.000
place to be.

00:06:22.799 --> 00:06:25.000
So we have different options here.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:27.399
Well, do we just throw away our static outputs and we only

00:06:27.399 --> 00:06:30.799
do dynamic because we feel like we have a very reproducible

00:06:30.799 --> 00:06:32.500
pathway? Probably not.

00:06:32.899 --> 00:06:35.799
Probably not tomorrow anyway, at least maybe in the future.

00:06:36.299 --> 00:06:38.799
So we need to think about maintaining this pathway where

00:06:38.799 --> 00:06:41.500
we're generating static reports because that is what our end

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:42.799
users want to consume.

00:06:43.100 --> 00:06:45.100
That's where collaboration often happens.

00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:46.399
So what do we do?

00:06:47.399 --> 00:06:50.500
If we're impatient, what we can do is make an alternative

00:06:50.500 --> 00:06:51.100
pathway.

00:06:51.700 --> 00:06:55.000
So the feeling, the experience for the statistician or for

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.200
the statistical programmer generating that report is fundamentally

00:06:58.200 --> 00:07:01.600
different, but the end consumer of that report has the same

00:07:01.600 --> 00:07:02.399
experience.

00:07:02.700 --> 00:07:05.700
So that enables us to make kind of this concept of stepwise

00:07:05.700 --> 00:07:10.399
or non-disruptive change so we can still have, you know, hope

00:07:10.399 --> 00:07:13.200
that we can improve on a much shorter timescale.

00:07:14.299 --> 00:07:17.100
And it's really not just about the code and I'll repeat this

00:07:17.100 --> 00:07:18.200
again in the next slide.

00:07:18.399 --> 00:07:21.200
For us, the code that what we're showing here is pretty

00:07:21.200 --> 00:07:23.899
simple and we're leveraging other packages like Office

00:07:23.899 --> 00:07:28.100
ORR, but the processes is what really helped us here, developing

00:07:28.100 --> 00:07:31.500
using good data science practices and bringing that forward

00:07:31.500 --> 00:07:34.899
with different stakeholders and generating what we call company

00:07:34.899 --> 00:07:36.200
compliant documents.

00:07:36.600 --> 00:07:39.000
If you're again, not maybe from a pharma industry, you might

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:40.299
say, what's that mean?

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:44.100
Basically, we have very strict templates that are Word document

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:47.700
templates that have very particular styling and very particular

00:07:47.700 --> 00:07:50.100
things that we need to put in certain places.

00:07:50.399 --> 00:07:54.399
So again, the manual editing of those documents is a slow and

00:07:54.399 --> 00:07:57.100
sometimes fussy process for us.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:02.299
So I want to talk about just one use case that we covered in

00:08:02.299 --> 00:08:03.200
this package.

00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:07.000
So we're talking about sample size estimation and the reporting

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:08.100
of that calculation.

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:11.200
So before we begin a clinical trial, the very logical thing

00:08:11.200 --> 00:08:13.799
for us to ask is how many people should we recruit?

00:08:14.100 --> 00:08:16.899
How many people should be on the different treatments or the

00:08:16.899 --> 00:08:20.000
different arms that we're going to have in our study to ensure

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.600
that the evidence that we generate is reliable, right?

00:08:22.799 --> 00:08:25.299
And there are lots of statistical methods that help us to do

00:08:25.299 --> 00:08:26.500
those calculations.

00:08:26.799 --> 00:08:29.200
And this is what our statisticians are doing, given what we

00:08:29.200 --> 00:08:31.000
know about the different studies that we're running.

00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:33.099
And they want to bring this together.

00:08:33.900 --> 00:08:37.599
So how we went about this is it was actually our statisticians

00:08:37.599 --> 00:08:38.299
who came to us.

00:08:38.299 --> 00:08:41.599
So I sit within a team that makes tools for our clinical

00:08:41.599 --> 00:08:44.400
trials teams and they were saying, I really don't like this

00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:45.200
part of my job.

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:46.000
It's frustrating.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:46.500
It's slow.

00:08:46.500 --> 00:08:47.400
It's a bottleneck.

00:08:47.500 --> 00:08:50.299
I feel like my work is not as reproducible as it could be.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:53.299
So we got them on board and we said, hey, let's think about

00:08:53.299 --> 00:08:54.099
this together.

00:08:54.400 --> 00:08:57.000
But let's also bring someone from our compliance department

00:08:57.299 --> 00:08:59.900
because we want to make sure whatever we do in the end is

00:08:59.900 --> 00:09:02.000
going to be something we can deploy and roll out.

00:09:02.099 --> 00:09:04.500
So let's get them on board from the very start as well.

00:09:04.799 --> 00:09:06.099
Let's design it together.

00:09:06.900 --> 00:09:09.400
Let's leverage the good software development practices that

00:09:09.400 --> 00:09:12.700
are so common in our teams, but maybe a little bit less common

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:14.299
for some of our other users.

00:09:14.799 --> 00:09:16.799
And let's not wait too long.

00:09:17.400 --> 00:09:19.400
So let's every two to three weeks show each other what we

00:09:19.400 --> 00:09:22.000
have and try to see, does it look like it's working?

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.200
Is that going to be a better experience for you?

00:09:24.900 --> 00:09:26.900
And bringing all of those things together, I think, helped

00:09:26.900 --> 00:09:29.799
us to do this in a matter of, you know, weeks to get to a

00:09:29.799 --> 00:09:30.599
first version.

00:09:32.099 --> 00:09:33.099
So what does it look like?

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:35.599
So we've done a lot of talking about what it might look like

00:09:35.900 --> 00:09:38.200
and I'm going to show you a couple of code snippets now and

00:09:38.200 --> 00:09:38.900
the outputs.

00:09:39.299 --> 00:09:42.299
So again, I think the goal to remember is people wanted to

00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:45.799
generate Microsoft Word documents, but never know, never

00:09:45.799 --> 00:09:47.200
have to go to that product.

00:09:48.099 --> 00:09:51.299
And this is really what we can do using a combination and

00:09:51.299 --> 00:09:53.500
for this particular use case, we used R Markdown.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.799
So we made classes, specifically R6 classes for every element

00:09:57.799 --> 00:10:00.599
of the report that we knew we wanted to create.

00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:04.000
And what that really helped us to do is to think really

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:05.500
carefully about the structure.

00:10:06.099 --> 00:10:08.099
So classes, they have attributes, right?

00:10:08.099 --> 00:10:11.200
So they have elements and then they have methods and you

00:10:11.200 --> 00:10:13.099
could think about these really separately.

00:10:13.099 --> 00:10:15.000
So we could all kind of be like, I'll take that class, you

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.200
take that class and you can work in a very nicely parallelized

00:10:18.200 --> 00:10:21.400
way and kind of a lot of your project management and your

00:10:21.599 --> 00:10:23.099
design is kind of done for you.

00:10:24.299 --> 00:10:28.000
So by simply filling out and initializing this class and

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:31.299
then doing our rendering in our getTitlePage method, we

00:10:31.299 --> 00:10:34.900
can actually produce our Word document title page in a way

00:10:34.900 --> 00:10:38.599
that is in the format that we expect it to be using all

00:10:38.599 --> 00:10:40.700
of the different fields that we wanted to have.

00:10:40.900 --> 00:10:43.099
So this was like a really exciting thing for us and this

00:10:43.099 --> 00:10:44.200
is energizing, right?

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:46.299
People were like, oh, this is cool because I hate doing

00:10:46.299 --> 00:10:49.099
that fab and they were getting on board because they were

00:10:49.099 --> 00:10:49.799
excited.

00:10:51.599 --> 00:10:53.599
It's the same thing for the different elements within the

00:10:53.599 --> 00:10:54.299
report.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:58.500
We created classes for things that had some unique properties

00:10:58.500 --> 00:11:01.099
that were like, hey, can't just make a general table, but

00:11:01.099 --> 00:11:03.599
here we can make a changelog table that's really easy to

00:11:03.599 --> 00:11:07.200
populate, add rows and then we can render that again.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:10.099
And we did that for all of the different elements across

00:11:10.099 --> 00:11:14.200
our report and eventually render the entire document.

00:11:14.200 --> 00:11:17.299
So what's underneath the hood here is a single or a markdown

00:11:17.299 --> 00:11:20.799
file and you can render that and it will produce your Word

00:11:20.799 --> 00:11:21.900
document at the end.

00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:25.099
The other very exciting thing is you could co-locate the

00:11:25.099 --> 00:11:27.099
document content with the calculation.

00:11:27.099 --> 00:11:30.299
So if you're using a package like orpact, which is commonly

00:11:30.299 --> 00:11:33.000
used in our company for general sample size calculations,

00:11:33.200 --> 00:11:35.799
everything's now in the one place and that makes us all

00:11:35.799 --> 00:11:39.099
feel really happy because if you want to go back to it, it's

00:11:39.099 --> 00:11:41.799
just one single document that is going to generate the Word

00:11:41.799 --> 00:11:44.500
document, but also reproduce the calculations should you

00:11:44.500 --> 00:11:46.400
want to do that and you want to revisit them.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:49.700
We also did a lot of logging here.

00:11:49.799 --> 00:11:52.299
Again, I think that makes us all feel pretty safe.

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:53.200
When did I do it?

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:54.000
Who did it?

00:11:54.400 --> 00:11:56.099
What was what kind of packages did I have?

00:11:56.099 --> 00:11:57.599
What was my session looking like?

00:11:57.900 --> 00:12:00.400
So again, we could do a lot of those logs so we could generate

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:03.700
a lot of that traceability again to kind of make sure that

00:12:03.700 --> 00:12:06.299
we felt we were kind of keeping all of the good practices

00:12:06.299 --> 00:12:08.799
that we had seen when we generate an output itself.

00:12:10.299 --> 00:12:11.000
And we end up here.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.599
I know this is a little bit small, but basically this is

00:12:14.599 --> 00:12:15.099
it, right?

00:12:15.099 --> 00:12:16.500
We get a whole document.

00:12:16.700 --> 00:12:19.400
It's a single or a markdown file and we never have to

00:12:19.400 --> 00:12:22.500
touch Microsoft Word or go in and edit it.

00:12:23.400 --> 00:12:26.299
And that was really exciting and to get to that point and

00:12:26.299 --> 00:12:29.000
I think again, it kind of brought in even more understanding

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:32.000
of I can see now what all this open source stuff can do

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.700
for me and isn't different to what I used to do before.

00:12:35.599 --> 00:12:37.599
But again, it wasn't just about the code, right?

00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:40.400
It was about thinking about how can we do this in a way

00:12:40.400 --> 00:12:42.700
that makes sense from a software perspective as well.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.099
So again, a report and at least in my mind, it really lends

00:12:46.099 --> 00:12:47.799
itself to being object-oriented.

00:12:47.799 --> 00:12:49.200
There's natural elements.

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:51.799
You need to have different methods for them, different

00:12:51.799 --> 00:12:55.400
attributes, and then you can do a lot with assertions.

00:12:55.900 --> 00:12:59.200
So assertions are before I'm going to make the class, I

00:12:59.200 --> 00:13:03.000
can assert what I think the values of these attributes

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:03.500
should be.

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:06.500
So I can say I want my date to have this format.

00:13:06.700 --> 00:13:08.799
If you don't give it to me in that format, I don't let

00:13:08.799 --> 00:13:09.700
you make your class.

00:13:09.900 --> 00:13:11.900
You have an error and you cannot go forward.

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:15.299
So that's a very kind of maybe strict approach.

00:13:15.299 --> 00:13:17.500
You can choose different flavors of how strict you want

00:13:17.500 --> 00:13:20.099
to be, but instead of then having to review a Word

00:13:20.099 --> 00:13:22.900
document to make sure the date looks like a date, you can

00:13:22.900 --> 00:13:23.799
do it upfront.

00:13:24.200 --> 00:13:26.500
So a lot of those things that we perhaps don't enjoy doing

00:13:26.500 --> 00:13:29.500
in our jobs, like a lot of that checking, we can automate

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:32.099
that in our approach as well, which I think, you know,

00:13:32.099 --> 00:13:34.599
makes us able to focus on different things.

00:13:37.400 --> 00:13:40.000
We also then as developers create a lot of tests for our

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.599
package and had a CICD pipeline.

00:13:43.099 --> 00:13:45.200
So we had lots of different people wanting to come in

00:13:45.200 --> 00:13:46.500
and work on our package as well.

00:13:46.500 --> 00:13:49.400
We wanted to make that open to them, right?

00:13:49.400 --> 00:13:53.000
So we couldn't scale to do every possible report in the

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:53.599
company.

00:13:53.900 --> 00:13:56.299
So as we want to work together, making sure that we have

00:13:56.299 --> 00:13:57.700
a lot of tests for every class.

00:13:57.700 --> 00:14:01.299
So if we change something, we know we either, the tests

00:14:01.299 --> 00:14:04.000
that we have passed, we need to add new tests or we've

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:04.799
broken something.

00:14:04.799 --> 00:14:07.299
So let's not put that to code review just yet.

00:14:07.700 --> 00:14:10.599
So that really helped us to have different people working

00:14:10.599 --> 00:14:13.400
on the package and making sure that we were able to test

00:14:13.400 --> 00:14:14.500
what we were doing as well.

00:14:16.900 --> 00:14:18.200
Okay, so now and next.

00:14:18.900 --> 00:14:21.799
So we've just finished successfully piloting this package

00:14:21.799 --> 00:14:24.400
for our sample size report within-house.

00:14:24.799 --> 00:14:26.500
We focus on two different scenarios.

00:14:26.500 --> 00:14:28.599
So what if someone was doing an amendment, if they'd never

00:14:28.599 --> 00:14:30.799
used the package before, what would that look like?

00:14:31.099 --> 00:14:33.500
Or if they were doing a brand new study, could they jump

00:14:33.500 --> 00:14:35.799
in and then what were the ways that they could jump in?

00:14:36.299 --> 00:14:39.599
And in both cases, this is where your compliance people

00:14:39.599 --> 00:14:40.500
are so helpful.

00:14:40.900 --> 00:14:44.200
Understanding if the report was different, if we were using

00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:46.700
a different version of the template, what will we need to

00:14:46.700 --> 00:14:48.599
document in terms of our process?

00:14:48.599 --> 00:14:49.599
Or does that look okay?

00:14:49.900 --> 00:14:53.000
So we had a very engaged compliant person, Maritza, to

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:54.200
really help us there as well.

00:14:54.900 --> 00:14:57.700
And we also have additional use cases that I didn't go

00:14:57.700 --> 00:15:00.900
through today, but some of our teams were saying sometimes

00:15:00.900 --> 00:15:04.299
something changes in the data and it's a small thing and

00:15:04.299 --> 00:15:08.500
then I need to edit 50 figures in a Word document and I

00:15:08.500 --> 00:15:09.299
don't want to do that.

00:15:09.299 --> 00:15:10.099
It's very manual.

00:15:10.099 --> 00:15:11.400
It takes me a lot of time.

00:15:11.799 --> 00:15:15.799
So simply with using a YAML to say, hey, this is where, this

00:15:15.799 --> 00:15:19.099
is the footer, was like the key, find that figure, update

00:15:19.099 --> 00:15:20.299
it with this new figure.

00:15:20.500 --> 00:15:23.099
We could also automate how people were updating their Word

00:15:23.099 --> 00:15:27.099
documents, which again is saving a lot of time and also

00:15:27.099 --> 00:15:29.900
is much less error prone than someone kind of going delete,

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.400
you know, copy, paste again, right?

00:15:32.799 --> 00:15:35.500
So it's all about making sure that we have a much more kind

00:15:35.500 --> 00:15:38.400
of traceable way to make those changes.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:41.599
We thought a lot about how we were going to open source

00:15:41.599 --> 00:15:44.700
this. It's kind of a funny one because it's very reliant

00:15:44.700 --> 00:15:46.299
on our company templates.

00:15:46.500 --> 00:15:49.400
So I'm very specific to what we're doing, but then equally

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:51.700
we didn't really want to just kind of keep this fully in

00:15:51.700 --> 00:15:54.900
house. So what we're working on now is just having a very

00:15:54.900 --> 00:15:58.299
generic document and showing how we developed our code to

00:15:58.299 --> 00:16:01.099
do this. As I said, I don't think the code basis is that

00:16:01.099 --> 00:16:03.799
extensive or complicated, but perhaps what we can do is

00:16:03.799 --> 00:16:05.700
include a lot of our CICD as well.

00:16:06.099 --> 00:16:09.200
So people can kind of, you know, take this, make their own

00:16:09.200 --> 00:16:11.700
version, but kind of keep some of those practices

00:16:11.700 --> 00:16:14.799
embedded. And we want to do even more use cases.

00:16:15.099 --> 00:16:17.599
So I think this is where our testing will come into play

00:16:17.599 --> 00:16:21.500
and we'll see how we can change the shape of it.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.400
But really we hope this is going to create a much more

00:16:24.900 --> 00:16:27.900
enjoyable experience for people who want to produce reports

00:16:27.900 --> 00:16:31.000
in this way without us having to wait a couple of years

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:32.700
to make these types of changes, right?

00:16:32.700 --> 00:16:37.099
So that's what we're really excited about. And I'm very

00:16:37.099 --> 00:16:40.099
grateful to the people I worked with at Novartis. A combination

00:16:40.099 --> 00:16:43.400
of people from different parts of Novartis coming to us

00:16:43.400 --> 00:16:46.799
saying, hey, change this, this needs to be better. And you

00:16:46.799 --> 00:16:49.299
know, when those people come to you, they bring you such

00:16:49.299 --> 00:16:52.799
valuable knowledge and you get like such great insight into

00:16:52.799 --> 00:16:55.599
how you can really help. And then also, as I said, people

00:16:55.599 --> 00:16:58.900
from compliance, they know how to get stuff done. Making

00:16:58.900 --> 00:17:01.700
friends with your compliance people and going together is

00:17:01.700 --> 00:17:04.500
really, really important so that whatever you develop

00:17:04.500 --> 00:17:07.099
has a very good chance of getting to the people you wanted

00:17:07.099 --> 00:17:09.800
to get to, right? It's always disappointing to find out

00:17:09.800 --> 00:17:13.099
at the end that perhaps you missed a step or it's going

00:17:13.099 --> 00:17:16.099
to take a while to edit an SOP or working practice.

00:17:16.099 --> 00:17:18.400
So good to get that done at the start as well.

00:17:19.099 --> 00:17:20.300
Yeah, so thank you very much.

00:17:27.599 --> 00:17:31.400
Thank you, Orla. Quickly, is Joshua Cook here? If so,

00:17:31.400 --> 00:17:32.699
could you please come to the front?

00:17:35.199 --> 00:17:39.300
So time for a couple questions. Top one here is, are the

00:17:39.300 --> 00:17:42.500
reports compliant with accessibility standards? And if

00:17:42.500 --> 00:17:45.599
so, how do you implement those accessibility elements? Not

00:17:45.599 --> 00:17:48.099
sure if it's relevant for Novartis, but. Yeah, no, I think

00:17:48.099 --> 00:17:51.500
it's a good question. I have to say, I think things like

00:17:51.500 --> 00:17:55.400
colorblindness for graphics and things like that are

00:17:55.400 --> 00:17:58.699
things that are important. But I think anything further

00:17:58.699 --> 00:18:00.300
than that, I have to say, I don't think it's something

00:18:00.300 --> 00:18:02.800
that we have actively checked in the documents, but it's

00:18:02.800 --> 00:18:05.900
a good question. I actually wrote that down because

00:18:05.900 --> 00:18:08.199
somebody said it at the Orin Pharma Summit, so I have

00:18:08.199 --> 00:18:10.199
it in my notes to be like, are we doing that?

00:18:12.199 --> 00:18:16.000
One more. How do you go about the exercise of scaling

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:19.300
this to preclinical or including other modeling results

00:18:19.300 --> 00:18:22.000
in such reports? Like what are the steps of the design

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:25.800
thinking? Yeah, so I think it's very simple to include

00:18:25.800 --> 00:18:28.800
different results or different code. I think where it

00:18:28.800 --> 00:18:32.400
is not always as scalable as we would like is if the

00:18:32.400 --> 00:18:36.099
templates look very different. Because then there

00:18:36.099 --> 00:18:38.599
is some limitations in how dynamically we can work

00:18:38.599 --> 00:18:42.599
with Docx and XML. So there's a little bit of

00:18:42.599 --> 00:18:45.300
setup if the template is really different for sure.

00:18:45.599 --> 00:18:48.500
But then if you have some type of generic report, I

00:18:48.500 --> 00:18:51.500
think that's going to scale extremely well. And the

00:18:51.500 --> 00:18:54.199
other thing is trying to get the people who want that

00:18:54.500 --> 00:18:57.900
in. And I think it's a brilliant opportunity. They

00:18:57.900 --> 00:19:00.300
have different skills than I do. I have different

00:19:00.300 --> 00:19:02.900
skills than they do. So kind of getting people from

00:19:02.900 --> 00:19:05.500
different parts of your business in, if they would

00:19:05.500 --> 00:19:07.800
be willing to adopt some of the software practices,

00:19:07.800 --> 00:19:10.300
you can kind of almost do that in a knowledge

00:19:10.300 --> 00:19:13.500
sharing as well. But I think getting folks to ideally

00:19:13.500 --> 00:19:16.000
come in as well and be part of the development is

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:17.500
I think how we can scale it as well.

00:19:18.599 --> 00:19:21.599
One more quick one. So I was thinking about like

00:19:21.599 --> 00:19:23.599
how you would work with your compliance people and

00:19:23.599 --> 00:19:25.199
like what does that look like? Because you're writing

00:19:25.199 --> 00:19:28.099
code, but then you produce an output. Then it's like

00:19:28.099 --> 00:19:30.000
you produce the output, you show it to them, you say

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:31.800
is this good? And then you do some tweaking and then

00:19:31.800 --> 00:19:33.900
is that the cycle that you go through with these

00:19:33.900 --> 00:19:36.500
people? No. So I would say that's more like

00:19:36.500 --> 00:19:39.000
statistician to statistician. So that would they

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:41.000
would be working together to say, hey, I have this

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:43.699
output. Can you double program it or can you

00:19:43.699 --> 00:19:47.099
verify it? The process of what that looks like is

00:19:47.099 --> 00:19:50.199
then designed with your compliance person. So what

00:19:50.199 --> 00:19:53.099
documentation do you need to have to kind of have

00:19:53.099 --> 00:19:56.099
evidence that you did that check? And then we would

00:19:56.099 --> 00:19:58.300
also work a lot with Moritz and say, well, the

00:19:58.300 --> 00:20:01.000
working practice for sample size reports is

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:03.300
currently like this. If we were to introduce or

00:20:03.300 --> 00:20:05.900
markdown, what needs to change, if anything. So

00:20:05.900 --> 00:20:08.199
she would help us a lot with the formal kind of

00:20:08.199 --> 00:20:11.300
documents in our company. And she always has a

00:20:11.300 --> 00:20:13.500
solution for many things. So a great person to

00:20:13.500 --> 00:20:16.099
work with as well. Yeah. Great. Thank you so much.

00:20:16.099 --> 00:20:16.599
Thanks, Luke.

00:20:23.099 --> 00:20:23.599
Thank you.

